1 Check if there is an SSH key on your PC
ls ~/.ssh
If you see something like:
id_ed25519
id_ed25519.pub
The key is there, let's move on
If not, create it

2Ô∏è Create an SSH key (if it doesn't exist)
ssh-keygen -t ed25519 -C "your_email@example.com"
The key will be created here:
~/.ssh/id_ed25519
~/.ssh/id_ed25519.pub

3Ô∏è Copy the key TO THE SERVER
ssh-copy-id user@SERVER_IP
example:
ssh-copy-id ubuntu@192.XXX.X.XXX
Enter the password LAST ONCE

4Ô∏è CHECK KEY access (very important)
OPEN A SECOND TERMINAL (don't close the first one)
ssh user@SERVER_IP
If you logged in WITHOUT a password ‚Äî perfect
If it asks for a password ‚Äî DO NOT GO ANY FURTHER

5Ô∏è MAKE A BACKUP OF SSH config (required)
On the server:
sudo cp /etc/ssh/sshd_config /etc/ssh/sshd_config.backup

6Ô∏è Disable password login
sudo nano /etc/ssh/sshd_config
Find or add:
PasswordAuthentication no
PubkeyAuthentication yes
Also recommend:
PermitRootLogin no
Save:
Ctrl + O
Enter
Ctrl + X

7Ô∏è Check the config (so as not to break SSH)
sudo sshd -t
If nothing output ‚Äî everything is fine
If there is an error ‚Äî DO NOT restart

8Ô∏è Restart SSH
sudo systemctl restart ssh

9Ô∏è FINAL CHECK (very important)
LOG OUT FROM THE SERVER
exit
LOG IN AGAIN
ssh user@SERVER_IP

‚úî Logged in without a password ‚Üí üéâ DONE
‚ùå Failed to log in ‚Üí return to backup
